{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"the-crusades","type":"era","content":{"title":"The Crusades","date_label":"1095 CE – 1291 CE","description":"The **Crusades** were a series of religious wars sanctioned by the Latin Church with the stated goal of recovering the Holy Land from Islamic rule. Pope Urban II's call at the Council of Clermont in 1095 launched the First Crusade, which succeeded in capturing Jerusalem in 1099.\n\nSubsequent Crusades met with mixed results. The **Third Crusade** (1189–1192) led by Richard I of England and Philip II of France failed to retake Jerusalem from Saladin, though it secured Christian access to the city. The **Fourth Crusade** (1202–1204) notoriously sacked Constantinople, permanently damaging relations between Latin and Eastern Christianity.\n\nThe era ended with the **fall of Acre** in 1291, the last major Crusader stronghold in the Holy Land. The Crusades left a complex legacy: they accelerated cultural exchange between Europe and the Islamic world, introduced new goods and ideas to the West, but also caused tremendous suffering and deep inter-religious wounds that persist to the present day.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["crusades","jerusalem","papacy","holy-land","medieval","religion"],"sources":[{"title":"Crusades — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Crusades"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"1095","end_value":"1291","precision":"year"},"significance":{"value":880,"temporal_scope":"centuries","geographic_scope":"europe-middle-east"}}}
